<subSubSection id="952C6BA0700CC3BC48BC9F0B62C09619" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="4" pageNumber="15" type="remark">
<paragraph id="839A6E0337A44A1DCE19B4DD6D3EEEE6" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DFD976F832294984CD2C3B956043620F" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">
The species of this genus have a high morphological plasticity and many species have been described. 
<bibRefCitation id="B93C4F21C839C7CF7EC2F25A84061EA3" author="Glaubrecht, M" journalOrPublisher="Miutteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Museum und Institut" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="41 - 97" refId="B21" refString="Glaubrecht, M, 1993. Mapping the diversity: Geographical distribution of the freshwater snail Melanopsis (Gastropoda: Cerithioidea: Melanopsidae) with focus on its systematics in Mediterranean basin. Miutteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Museum und Institut 90: 41 - 97" title="Mapping the diversity: Geographical distribution of the freshwater snail Melanopsis (Gastropoda: Cerithioidea: Melanopsidae) with focus on its systematics in Mediterranean basin." volume="90" year="1993">Glaubrecht (1993)</bibRefCitation>
tried to solve the complicated taxonomy by proposing to consider all circum-Mediterranean 
<taxonomicName id="B8096029A99E65A776DE9AB3090978BF" authorityName="Glöer &amp; Pešić" authorityYear="2012" class="Gastropoda" family="Melanopsidae" genus="Melanopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="[unassigned] Caenogastropoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7649FF3F6A06B5CA038F237B909374A3" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Melanopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. as being part of one 
<normalizedToken id="6FEE5A70852644228470135F3ED49CC0" originalValue="‘superspecies’">'superspecies'</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BDE075362862AFD6EC279ADBE917D9D9" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Gastropoda" family="Melanopsidae" genus="Melanopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="[unassigned] Caenogastropoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="praemorsa">
<emphasis id="3B74395C7DBFB4C88ECCC32AFEA64A42" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Melanopsis praemorsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, we follow 
<bibRefCitation id="D5B70921A290819CAC27744ECB9F6D3D" author="Neubert, E" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Arabia" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="333 - 461" refId="B46" refString="Neubert, E, 1998. Annotated checklist of the terrestrial and freshwater molluscs of the Arabian Peninsula with description of new species. Fauna of Arabia 17: 333 - 461" title="Annotated checklist of the terrestrial and freshwater molluscs of the Arabian Peninsula with description of new species." volume="17" year="1998">Neubert (1998)</bibRefCitation>
who believes that this approach does not solve the problem. In recent literature the 
<normalizedToken id="A8FFAA58646B3572688476DA54B60707" originalValue="‘superspecies’">'superspecies'</normalizedToken>
notion tends to be abandoned and the former species names are being reinstituted (see: 
<bibRefCitation id="E4D0EF415D316E2B06BCF2C170F9E0F0" author="Heller, J" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="229 - 260" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1096-3642.2005.00172.x" refId="B30" refString="Heller, J, Mordan, P, Ben-Ami, F, Sivan, N, 2005. Conchometrics, systematics and distribution of Melanopsis (Mollusca: Gastropoda) in the Levant. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 144 (2): 229 - 260, 10.1111/j.1096-3642.2005.00172.x" title="Conchometrics, systematics and distribution of Melanopsis (Mollusca: Gastropoda) in the Levant." url="10.1111/j.1096-3642.2005.00172.x" volume="144" year="2005">Heller et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C62CF6619CEC7530C41B4845221BD68E" author="van Damme, D" editor="Garcia, N" journalOrPublisher="Gland, Switzerland, Cambridge, UK and Malaga, Spain, IUCN, Occasional Paper of the IUCN Species Survival Commission (ISBN: 978 - 2 - 8317 - 1271 - 0), Chapter 4" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="30 - 49" refId="B16" refString="van Damme, D, Ghamizi, M, Soliman, G, McIvor, A, Seddon, M, 2010. The status and distribution of freshwater molluscs. In: Garcia, N, Cuttelod, A, Abdul Malak, D, Eds., The status and distribution of freshwater biodiversity in Northern Africa. Gland, Switzerland, Cambridge, UK and Malaga, Spain, IUCN, Occasional Paper of the IUCN Species Survival Commission (ISBN: 978-2-8317-1271-0), Chapter 4: 30 - 49" title="The status and distribution of freshwater molluscs." volumeTitle="The status and distribution of freshwater biodiversity in Northern Africa." year="2010">Van Damme et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
. This means that the smooth unsculptured species 
